{{Infobox film |name = Basta't Kasama Kita |image = Basta't Kasama Kita poster.jpg |caption = Theatrical release poster |director = [[Rory B. Quintos]] |producer = |screenplay = {{Plainlist| *Jerry Lopez Sineneng *Mel Mendoza-Del Rosario *Don Cuaresma *[[Olivia M. Lamasan]] }} |story = {{Plainlist| *Jerry Lopez Sineneng *Olivia M. Lamasan }} |starring = {{Plainlist| *[[Aga Muhlach]] *[[Dayanara Torres]] }} |music = Nonong Buencamino |cinematography = Joe Batac, Jr. |editing = Jess Navarro |studio = [[Star Cinema]] |distributor = Star Cinema |released = {{Film date|1995|2|1}} |runtime = |country = Philippines |language = {{unbulleted list|Filipino|English}} |budget = }}
'''''Basta't Kasama Kita''''' ({{literal translation|"As Long As I'm with You"}}) is a 1995 Philippine [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Rory B. Quintos]] on her feature film [[directorial debut]].<ref name="pep">{{cite news|title=Director Cathy Garcia Molina does not want to work with big stars|url=http://www.pep.ph/lifestyle/18557/director-cathy-garcia-molina-does-not-want-to-work-with-big-stars|language=Filipino|accessdate=August 3, 2017|work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=March 19, 2009|quote=Ang huli ko pong pagsasama kay Aga, yung Basta't Kasama Kita. AD [assistant director] po ako doon. First movie ni Direk Rory [Quintos], with Dayanara Torres. It was...mga 1995.}}</ref> Starring [[Aga Muhlach]] and [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] actress and [[Miss Universe 1993]] [[Dayanara Torres]], the film follows Marinella (Torres), a European royalty who longs for an independent life by plotting a [[royal visit]] to the [[Philippines]] and then escape her security detail. In the Philippines she accidentally meets Alex (Muhlach), a [[jeepney]] driver who agrees to her plea to work as a housemaid in exchange for food and shelter; the two suddenly fall for each other.<ref>{{cite news|title=DIGITALLY RESTORED AND REMASTERED "BASTA’T KASAMA KITA"AIRS ON SUNDAY’S BEST AND SKYDIRECT FREE VIEW|url=http://abscbnpr.com/digitally-restored-and-remastered-bastat-kasama-kitaairs-on-sundays-best-and-skydirect-free-view/|accessdate=3 August 2017|work=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs]]|date=January 27, 2017}}</ref> The plot is similar to that of the 1953 film ''[[Roman Holiday]]'', which starred [[Audrey Hepburn]] and [[Gregory Peck]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aga Muhlach, Dayanara Torres willing to work together again|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/content/22618/aga-muhlach-dayanara-torres-willing-to-work-together-again/story/|accessdate=August 3, 2017|work=[[GMA News and Public Affairs]]|date=December 2, 2006}}</ref>
In a 2017 retrospective by [[CNN Philippines]], ''Basta't Kasama Kita'' was selected as one of the best romantic-comedy films in the last 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 25 best Filipino rom-coms of the last 25 years|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/life/entertainment/film/2017/08/04/25-best-romcoms-list.html|accessdate=October 16, 2017|work=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=August 4, 2017}}</ref>
==Plot== The films begins with a banquet for Princess Marinella of Bavaria (Dayanara Torres), she was invited as a speaker for the International Year of the Child. However, Ella is not living as a princess and wanted an independent life.
Meanwhile, in the slums of Manila, Alex (Aga Muhlach) adopted half-brother Paolo (Paolo Contis) who is now an orphan. Ella wanted to go around Manila, but was barred by security men. She sought the help of her Aunt Belle (Heather Rasch). The following day, Ella disguised herself as Ms. Thompson, however several havocks came, until she left out of the hotel. There she and Alex met.
